How to Grow on Twitch¶

By: Matthew Simmons

Introduction¶

Next month will mark 10 years since Twitch.tv was introduced to the Internet. Twitch.tv is a live streaming service that focuses on video games and esports competitions, although it also offers a variety of other content. Since then, many things have changed on Twitch - particularly in its popularity. Many people, back then and now, have begun to stream on Twitch - either as a side passion or as a full-time job. For these people, it is important to understand how to grow their community and outreach in order to make money - it's their livelihood! We will answer the long-standing question of how to grow on Twitch so that we may be able to become a large Twitch stream someday.

Data Collection¶

It is important that we gather trustworthy and reliable data points for our project. Why would be check the statistics of the average breadbaker if we are trying to grow popular? For this reason, we will be analyzing a subset of Twitch streamers based on how large and successful they are - that is, we will gather data from the top Twitch streamers and use this to base our analysis on.

Initially, I looked through the data provided by the final project's specifications and found this kaggle source: https://www.kaggle.com/aayushmishra1512/twitchdata. This source has data on the Top 1000 Twitch streamers based on watch time. Unfortunately, I could not find much use in it, as most data gathered are uncontrollable factors (e.g., average viewership, total followers, whether they're partnered, etc.) and we are trying to figure out what we can do to maximize our viewers. I continued to search on Kaggle, and I found another similar set of data: https://www.kaggle.com/girlazo/top-8800-twitch-streamers. This data set is essentially the same as the above set, but it has two important differences that make it desirable. First, there are more controllable factors, which we will get into in the data analysis. Second, this data set has the top 8800 Twitch streamers rather than the top 1000. This is important because the lower rankings are more realistic - comparing with the other, lower numbers will help us see realistically what we can control, as it is possible the largest people got big through unconventional means such as luck.

Libraries¶

I imported several libraries for this project. The purpose of this is to make our lives easier in terms of data management and visualization.

  • Pandas: This is used to organize data into manipulable tables called dataframes.
  • Numpy: This gives us access to several ways to manipulate the data. I mostly use to to plot regression lines.
  • Matplotlib: This is used to take in data sets and turn them into visual plots.
  • Seaborn: This works in conjunction with Matplotlib to create other kinds of plots. Also, its plots are more visually appealing.
  • Statsmodels.api: This is the library we will use to perform our linear regression.
  • Sklearn.tree: This will allow us to create a Decision Tree.

Loading the Data¶

On Kaggle, we are able to download the datasets into a CSV file. From there, we can input that file and put it inside a dataframe. This allows us to manipulate our data.

# These two are not useful to us at all, pictures are links and complete_name is just another name.
df = df.drop(columns=['picture', 'complete_name'])

The data is split into several columns:

  • Ranking: This represents the ranking of how popular the Twitch streamer is. This set of data goes from 1 to 8800.
  • Name: This is the name of each Twitch streamer. It is how we can identify each row of data.
  • Watch time: This represents the number of total minutes people have watched of the Twitch streamer in the past year.
  • Stream time: This is how long, in minutes, the streamer would spend live on Twitch in the past year. This is a controllable factor.
  • Max viewers: This is the largest amount of concurrent viewers the streamer has had on Twitch.
  • Average viewers: This is the average number of concurrent viewers are streamer has had on their live streams.
  • Total followers: This holds the number of "followers" a streamer has. These are the people who chose to be notified whenever the particular streamer has gone live.
  • Delta followers: This is the change in the number of followers in the past year for a particular streamer.
  • Delta viewers: This is the change in the number of viewers in the past year for the streamer. This is what we want to maximize as a growing Twitch streamer!
  • Partnered: This represents whether or not the streamer is a Twitch partner. These are creators who have a sizeable audience and wish to monetize their streams. Since we have a list of top streamers, the vast majority is True.
  • Mature: This is whether the streamer creates kid-friendly content. This is a controllable factor.
  • Language: This is the language mostly spoken on the Twitch channel. Since Twitch is an American service, the majority is English. This is a controllable factor.
  • Cat 1: This is the streamer's most used streaming category. This represents the kind of content being streamed, e.g. which game or what activity. This is a controllable factor.
  • Cat 2: This is the secondmost used streaming category. This is a controllable factor.
  • Cat 3: This is the thirdmost used streaming category. This is a controllable factor.

Analysis & Visualization¶

Now, it is time to analyze the data. For the most part, we will be analyzing only the controllable factors (it doesn't help us to find a correlation with something we can't apply or use!). These are maturity, stream time, language (somewhat), and the streaming categories. One can argue that a change in followers can be controlled by using bot accounts.

First, let us compare with maturity: does being a mature-rated streamer yield more or less viewers? To compare, we will plot the distributions of both mature streamers and kid-friendly streamers.

In [4]:
viewers_on_maturity = [[], []]

# For clarity in the plots, we remove the extremely large outlier - the plots are useless if it is included!
# It is still included in the overall analysis.
df2 = df[df['delta_viewers'] != df['delta_viewers'].max()]

for (i, series) in df2.iterrows():
    viewers_on_maturity[1 if series['mature'] else 0].append(series['delta_viewers'])
    
plt.violinplot(viewers_on_maturity, [1, 2], showmeans=True);
plt.xticks([1, 2], ['All Audiences', 'Mature Audiences'])
plt.ylabel('Increase in Viewership')
plt.title('Maturity vs Increase in Viewers');

The two violin plots have roughly the same shape. However, the mean increase in viewers appears to be larger in the kid-friendly plot. It appears that mature streamers gain less viewers than the kid-friendly ones. Intuitively, this makes sense: the kid-friendly streamers simply have a larger pool of people to have view their streams.

Next, let us look at stream time. Is there a significant increase in the viewership of the streamer when they stream more?

In [5]:
ax = df2.plot.scatter(x='stream_time', y='delta_viewers')

# Creating regression line
plot = np.poly1d(np.polyfit(df2['stream_time'], df2['delta_viewers'], 1))
df2.insert(3, 'reg', plot(df2['stream_time']))
df2.plot(x='stream_time', y='reg', ax = ax, c = 'r', title='Minutes Streamed vs Increase in Viewers');

From this scatter plot, we can see that there is a positive trend in the data - however, it is not enough to conclude anything here.

Next, we will look at the increase in followers: do more followers lead to more viewers?

In [6]:
ax = df2.plot.scatter(x='delta_followers', y='delta_viewers')

# Creates the regression line
plot = np.poly1d(np.polyfit(df2['delta_followers'], df2['delta_viewers'], 1))
df2.insert(3, 'reg2', plot(df2['delta_followers']))
df2.plot(x='delta_followers', y='reg2', ax = ax, c = 'r', title='Increase in Followers vs Increase in Viewers');

Once again, there is a positive, linear relationship between an increase in followers and an increase in viewers. We will observe later how strong it is.

Now, we want to map all of our numerical data to see what is likely to impact the change in viewership. To do this, we can use a heatmap on the pairwise correlations of the data columns. Here, red means a high positive correlation, blue a high negative, and white no correlation. More intense colors mean a stronger correlation. For more information on correlation matrices, see https://www.displayr.com/what-is-a-correlation-matrix/.

In [7]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.heatmap(df.corr(method='kendall'), annot=True, cmap = 'coolwarm');

Unfortunately, this tells us that there is little correlation between the change in viewers and the controllable factors we have tried so far. The one with the highest correlation is delta_followers, so we will continue to use this in the Machine Learning section.

Now, let us take a look at the non-numerical data. First, we will take a look at language: how does the stream's language impact the increase in viewership?

This is much more helpful to interpret. From the plot above we can see that the languages with the largest increase in followers is Russian, followed by Thai, Turkish, and Chinese. English is directly below these four.

Now let's take a look at another divisive part of Twitch: the streaming category. Let's see which categories lead to a larger increase in viewers. Due to the large number of categories on Twitch, we will only display the top 100 categories ranked by the increase in viewership.

The top category for increase in viewers is Summer Game Fest. This is not helpful, as this is an online event that only The Game Awards may choose as the category. What is surprising is the number of non-traditional games that are among the top of the list: Warhammer, Dungeons & Dragons, and Chess are in the top 5 categories, although they are tabletop games. This is among several of the top categories which are not traditional: Twitch Plays, GeoGuessr, and Fitness & Health are is the top 10 categories. What's also interesting to note is that Just Chatting, arguably the largest non-traditional category, is all the way down as number 42 in the list.

Other than these, the largest of the standard gaming categories are at the top: Sports games such as FIFA, FPS games such as Call of Duty, and racing games such as Formula One are in the top 10.

Now, let's take a look to see if a second category is a noticeable difference in terms of viewers from the first.

Machine Learning¶

We have seen several potential driving factors of increasing Twitch viewership, namely an increase in followers, language, and Twitch category. Now, we will model these and see how well these act as predictors. Unfortunately due to the vast size of the number of categories, we will not be able to consider the streaming categories as an option (sklearn is currently working on an implementation regarding this: https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn/pull/12866). Because of this, we will stick to the other two potentially significant columns: increase in followers and language. I have decided to try both a Linear Regression Model and a Decision Tree Model.

Regression¶

We implement our linear regression using an OLS, which is the traditional least-squares regression (https://www.statisticshowto.com/probability-and-statistics/statistics-definitions/least-squares-regression-line/). Notice that when converting our categorical languages to other variables, we drop the first value in order to avoid the dummy variable trap and have too many variables.

In [13]:
temp_df = df2.copy()

temp_df = temp_df[temp_df['language'] != 'Other']

temp_df = temp_df[pd.notnull(temp_df['language'])]
temp_df = temp_df[pd.notnull(temp_df['delta_followers'])]

language_features = pd.get_dummies(temp_df.language, drop_first=True, prefix='lang')

standard_features = temp_df[['delta_followers', 'delta_viewers']]

concat_features = pd.concat([standard_features, language_features], axis=1)

languages = temp_df.language.unique().tolist()

# Arabic is our dummy value
for l in filter(lambda x: (x != 'Arabic'), languages):
    concat_features['followers*'+l] = concat_features['lang_'+l] * concat_features['delta_followers']

X = sm.add_constant(concat_features.drop('delta_viewers', axis=1))
y = concat_features['delta_viewers']

results = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

results.summary()

plt.violinplot(y - y_hat, showmeans=True)
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.title('Linear Regression Residuals');

This plot shows the residual of our model, or how far off we typically are. Contrary to the previous data, our residuals are centered at 0 and is unimodal. It is very possible that our model is actually quite good on the smaller-scale, only failing a large amount for the extremely large, top 100 streamers.

Decision Tree¶

Decision Trees are created out of a sequence of binary questions, i.e. questions with 2 answers. The ability to learn from these gets the answer quite quickly, making it a widely used model. For more, see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_tree.

Here, we create such a tree. We then run through sample tests and score the accuracy of the tree.

In [16]:
# Creates 2 sets of data - training data and testing data - by splitting the data 30/70.
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 2)

tree1 = tree.DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=15)

# Fits the data to the tree
tree1.fit(X_train, y_train)

acc = tree1.score(X_train, y_train)
score = tree1.score(X_test, y_test)

print("Accuracy in Training: " + str(acc))
print("Accuracy in Tests: " + str(score))

Accuracy in Training: 0.8272400144532557
Accuracy in Tests: -0.10492644166928677

Here, we see some interesting scores. Our model is able to accurately predict 83% of the data it was taught - better than the average student. However, it is not very good at testing other data, as it has a -10% accuracy in this.

Because both models are not very accurate, we can say that there is little correlation between language and increase in followers with the increase in a streamer's viewership.

Conclusion¶

In this tutorial, we looked through various ways of connecting top Twitch streamer's data to their ability to gain viewers. We explored these using a heat map, scatter plots, violin plots, and bar plots. We then took an idea and applied the methods of machine learning to it - we checked whether language and followers had a correlation with the number of viewers a streamer has. This was done with two different methods, a linear regression model and a decision tree model. Both models told us that there was little correlation between them. We have left category unexplored due to a lack of implementation in our chosen packages.

When it comes to small streamers, sometimes they are tempted to buy followers from a bot creator, someone who will have bot accounts follow you. Based on our model, we can see that unfortunately, these people are definitely running a scam business - the followers will have little-to-no impact on growing viewers naturally. Instead, the most probable method to growing viewers must be to look through the Twitch categories. If we can play all the most popular games, we will be able to form a great community.
